<p>South Carolina's humid subtropical climate creates specific HVAC requirements that differ significantly from other regions. The state experiences hot, humid summers with average temperatures reaching 85-90¬∞F and humidity levels often exceeding 70%. This combination places heavy demands on air conditioning systems for both cooling and dehumidification from May through September. Cooling loads typically account for 60-70% of annual residential energy consumption, making efficient HVAC systems critical for managing electricity costs.</p>

<p>The extended cooling season means HVAC systems operate intensively for 5-6 months annually, requiring robust equipment capable of handling sustained high-load conditions. Humidity control becomes equally important as temperature control, as inadequate dehumidification can lead to comfort issues and indoor air quality problems. Heat pumps perform exceptionally well in South Carolina's climate, providing efficient cooling during summers and adequate heating during mild winters when temperatures rarely drop below 30¬∞F for extended periods.</p>

<p>Coastal areas face additional challenges from salt air exposure, requiring corrosion-resistant equipment and more frequent maintenance. The Upstate region experiences slightly more heating demand due to higher elevations and cooler winter temperatures, while the Lowcountry focuses primarily on cooling and dehumidification. Proper system sizing becomes critical, as oversized units cycle frequently and fail to adequately remove humidity, while undersized systems struggle to maintain comfort during peak summer conditions.</p>

