<h2>South Carolina Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>South Carolina offers some of the most attractive solar incentives in the Southeast, significantly reducing the financial barriers to solar adoption. The federal Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit for solar installations completed through 2032, with the credit stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the total system cost including equipment, installation, and associated electrical work, representing substantial savings for most installations.</p>

<p>The South Carolina Solar Energy Tax Credit provides an additional 25% state tax credit, capped at \$5,250 per residential installation or 50% of tax liability, whichever is less. This state credit can be carried forward for up to 10 years if it exceeds annual tax liability, making it accessible to taxpayers across income levels. When combined with the federal credit, these incentives can reduce total system costs by up to 55%, dramatically improving project economics and payback periods.</p>

<p>Duke Energy South Carolina offers additional rebates through their renewable energy programs, including rebates up to \$1,000 for residential solar installations and \$500 for battery storage systems. The utility's net metering program allows solar customers to receive retail rate credits for excess electricity fed back to the grid, effectively using the utility grid as a virtual battery. Net metering credits roll over month-to-month and are paid out annually at avoided-cost rates, providing additional value for oversized systems.</p>

<p>For HVAC systems, South Carolina participates in various federal and utility rebate programs. Duke Energy offers rebates up to \$300 for high-efficiency heat pumps and up to \$150 for programmable thermostats. The federal Inflation Reduction Act provides tax credits up to \$2,000 for qualifying heat pump installations and additional rebates for income-qualified households. These programs can reduce HVAC upgrade costs by \$500-2,000 depending on equipment selection and household income levels.</p>

<p>Property tax exemptions add another layer of financial benefits for solar installations. South Carolina exempts the added value of solar energy systems from property tax assessments, ensuring that solar investments don't increase annual property tax obligations. This exemption applies to both residential and commercial installations and remains in effect for the system's lifetime, providing ongoing savings beyond the initial tax credits.</p>

